SIMPLE: shriek
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shriek
<hw>Shriek</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Shrieked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Shrieking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>shriken</ets>, originallythe same word as E. <ets>screech</ets>.
See <er>Screech</er>, and cf. <er>Screak</er>.]</ety> <def>To utter a
loud, sharp, shrill sound or cry, as do some birds and beasts; to
scream, as in a sudden fright, in horror or anguish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was the owl that <qex>shrieked</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At this she <qex>shrieked</qex> aloud; the mournful train⟦br⟧
Echoed her grief.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shriek</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shriek
<hw>Shriek</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To utter sharply and
shrilly; to utter in or with a shriek or shrieks.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On top whereof aye dwelt the ghostly owl,⟦br⟧
<qex>Shrieking</qex> his baleful note.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She <qex>shrieked</qex> his name⟦br⟧
To the dark woods.</q> <rj><qau>Moore.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shriek</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Shriek
<hw>Shriek</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A sharp, shrill outcry or scream; a
shrill wild cry such as is caused by sudden or extreme terror, pain, or
the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Shrieks</qex>, clamors, murmurs, fill the frighted town.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Shriek owl</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>The screech owl</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The swift; -- so called from
its cry.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shrieker</ent>⟦br⟧
